<DOC><DOCNO> AP890901-0058 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-89 0816EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-Israel-Lebanon     09-01 0347</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Israel-Lebanon,0360</SECOND><HEAD>Israeli Troops Kill Guerrilla Near Lebanese Border</HEAD><DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Israeli troops clashed today with severalguerrillas in Israel's self-declared security zone in south Lebanon.An army spokesman said one guerrilla was killed and two escaped.   Security sources in Lebanon said a fourth gunman may have escapedafter being wounded in the clash.   During the fighting, two Soviet-made Katyusha rockets exploded innorthern Israel causing no damage, security sources said. Therockets were apparently fired from outside the security zone nearthe area of the clash.   The clash happened before dawn near the village of Beit Yahun,six miles northwest of the Israeli border, said an Israeli armyspokesman, who requested anonymity in line with military regulations.   The spokesman said the dead gunman carried a Soviet-made AK-47assault rifle and large amounts of ammunition and plastic explosives.   Later, soldiers showed reporters the body of the dead guerrilla,who was wearing a camouflage uniform. The soldiers also showed threeKalashnikov assault guns, two of which apparently belonged to theescaped fighters.   On Thursday, another round of Katyusha rockets struck near ahouse in northern Israel smashing windows but causing no injuries.   Military spokesmen said they did not know which militia theguerrilla killed today may have belonged to.   The last attack in the security zone was on August 9, when asuicide car bomb carrying 550 pounds of explosives was detonatednear an Israeli military convoy, wounding five Israeli troops and anallied Lebanese militiaman. Two men in the car were killed.   Hezbollah, the Shiite Moslem fundamentalist militia, claimedresponsibility for the attack and said it was in retalitation forIsrael's kidnapping of a pro-Iranian Lebanese clergyman. Israelitroops abducted Shiite cleric Sheik Abdel Karim Obeid from his homein south Lebanon. Israeli troops along the northern border have beenon alert in anticipation of Hezbollah attacks.   Israel created the security zone in 1985 as a buffer zone afterwithdrawing the bulk of its force following a three-year occupation.   The 2-to-12-mile-wide zone is patrolled by Israeli soldiers andthe 2,500-member Israeli-supported South Lebanon Army militia.</TEXT></DOC>